📘 Coin Change Problem using Greedy, Dynamic Programming & Hybrid Approach
1. Abstract

The Coin Change Problem is a classic optimization problem in computer science that focuses on finding the minimum number of coins required to make a given amount using a set of coin denominations.

This project implements three different approaches — Greedy, Dynamic Programming (DP), and a Hybrid approach — to compare their efficiency and correctness. While the Greedy method provides faster solutions, it may fail to produce optimal results for certain inputs. Dynamic Programming guarantees optimality but at a higher computational cost.

The Hybrid approach combines the advantages of both methods to ensure correctness while maintaining efficiency. The project also includes an interactive visualization tool to enhance understanding.

2. Introduction

Optimization problems are fundamental in algorithm design, and the Coin Change Problem is one of the most widely studied examples. It has real-world applications in areas such as financial systems, vending machines, and resource allocation.

This project demonstrates how different algorithmic strategies behave under the same problem conditions. It highlights the importance of choosing the right approach depending on constraints like time complexity and correctness.

